    {
      "id": "955",
      "topic": "Art",
      "source": "The Verge AI",
      "shortTitle": "AI \u0026 Copyright",
      "mediumTitle": "US Supreme Court on AI Art",
      "longTitle": "AI-Generated Art Not Copyrightable",
      "paragraphs": [
        {
          "Lines": [
            "The courts determined that \u0027authorship\u0027",
            "in copyright law requires human creative",
            "input.",
            "The legal precedent established is that",
            "AI-generated works lacking demonstrable",
            "human authorship are not copyrightable",
            "in the US.",
            "On Monday, the US Supreme Court decided",
            "not to hear *Thaler v. Perlmutter*, a",
            "case concerning AI-generated artwork",
            "copyright.",
            "This decision does not impact copyright",
            "issues related to works *assisted* by",
            "AI, where humans have creative control.",
            "The Supreme Court\u2019s refusal to hear the",
            "case leaves the existing legal framework",
            "regarding AI and copyright unchanged.",
            "The case specifically addresses works",
            "created *solely* by an AI system,",
            "without human intervention."
          ]
        }
      ],
      "publishedAt": "2026-03-02T13:58:05.000Z",
      "ranking": 0,
      "articleUrl": "https://www.theverge.com/policy/887678/supreme-court-ai-art-copyright"
    },
